Healthy, wholesome and delicious soup that makes enough for leftovers and extra stock to freeze. | ifoodreal.com\" width=\"596\" height=\"900\" srcset=\"https://ifoodreal.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/buckwheat-soup-leftover-turkey-recipe-6.jpg 596w, https://ifoodreal.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/buckwheat-soup-leftover-turkey-recipe-6-199x300.jpg 199w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 596px) 100vw, 596px\">\n<p>At Easter dinner, I was given a turkey carcass (thank you, Katie – you know me oh so well). It came from a large turkey that fed over 20 people, with a substantial amount of meat on it. How could I say “no”?!</p>\n<p>I can’t stop but compare my life <a href=\"http://ifoodreal.com/growing-up-in-ukraine/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">“before”</a> and <a href=\"http://ifoodreal.com/immigrating-canada/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">“after”</a>.&nbsp;Yes, even a turkey carcass does that to me, yes. A carcass from my childhood had no meat on it, just bones, which was used for making 2 soups. You boil the carcass so many times until its broth has almost no floating fat bubbles. Meat of the carcass is stretched to make a filling for a massive amount of bliny, pirogies or stuffed potato patties.</p>\n<p>A turkey carcass of my 30s has enough meat for me to nibble on while preparing the turkey&nbsp;stock to cook, after it is cooked, to make the buckwheat soup for 4 people to eat twice, and to freeze another stock with meat for making soup #2. Whoa, that is so much food!</p>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-28558\" src=\"http://ifoodreal.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/buckwheat-soup-leftover-turkey-recipe-7.jpg\" alt=\"Give Ukrainian Buckwheat Soup Recipe with leftover turkey carcass, vegetables and kasha a chance. Healthy, wholesome and delicious soup that makes enough for leftovers and extra stock to freeze. | ifoodreal.com\" width=\"596\" height=\"900\" srcset=\"https://ifoodreal.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/buckwheat-soup-leftover-turkey-recipe-7.jpg 596w, https://ifoodreal.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/buckwheat-soup-leftover-turkey-recipe-7-199x300.jpg 199w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 596px) 100vw, 596px\">\n<p>Buckwheat soup might be something you have never heard of and I feel like it is my duty to share with you. I understand it is “different” and something that will never get 10,000 saves on Pinterest, but I’m living new me this year and blogging true myself, and doing what feels right. And right thing to do right now is to introduce you to a buckwheat soup.</p>\n<p>Because I feel like quinoa is so boring by now, and you will never ever get the same flavour from quinoa as you get from buckwheat in a soup!</p>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-28553\" src=\"http://ifoodreal.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/buckwheat-soup-leftover-turkey-recipe-2.jpg\" alt=\"Give Ukrainian Buckwheat Soup Recipe with leftover turkey carcass, vegetables and kasha a chance. Healthy, wholesome and delicious soup that makes enough for leftovers and extra stock to freeze. | ifoodreal.com\" width=\"596\" height=\"900\" srcset=\"https://ifoodreal.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/buckwheat-soup-leftover-turkey-recipe-2.jpg 596w, https://ifoodreal.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/buckwheat-soup-leftover-turkey-recipe-2-199x300.jpg 199w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 596px) 100vw, 596px\">\n<p>I always have wondered why and how quinoa caught such a popularity in a health world during the last 7 years? Why not buckwheat, it takes the same 15 minutes to cook (one of the quinoa’s benefits&nbsp;over brown&nbsp;rice)? Do you know what makes certain health food popular? I would love to hear your thoughts. <a href=\"https://ifoodreal.com/buckwheat-soup-leftover-turkey/\" class=\"more-link\">Read more »</a></p>\n\n  </section> <!-- end article section -->\n\n
